    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the EV vs Gas Cost Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our EV vs gas comparison calculator provides a comprehensive side-by-side cost analysis. Enter your annual driving miles, comparison period, and the details for both a gas vehicle (price, MPG, gas price, maintenance) and an electric vehicle (price, efficiency, electricity rate, maintenance). The calculator computes annual fuel costs, total ownership costs, cost per mile, break-even timeline, and annual CO2 emissions for both vehicles.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tool helps you make an informed decision by looking beyond the sticker price to the total cost picture. While EVs often have higher purchase prices, their significantly lower fuel and maintenance costs can make them cheaper to own over time. The break-even calculation shows exactly when the EV becomes the more economical choice.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Economics of EV vs Gas Ownership</h2>
      <p>
        The financial comparison between electric and gas vehicles involves several factors that shift the balance. On the operating cost side, EVs consistently win: electricity costs 60-70% less than gasoline per mile, and maintenance runs 30-50% less due to fewer moving parts. However, EVs typically carry a $5,000-$15,000 price premium over comparable gas models. Federal tax credits of up to $7,500 and various state incentives narrow this gap significantly.
      </p>

      <h3>Fuel Cost Comparison</h3>
      <p>
        Fuel cost is where EVs shine brightest. At $3.50 per gallon and 28 MPG, a gas car costs about $0.125 per mile to fuel. An EV using 30 kWh per 100 miles at $0.13 per kWh costs only $0.039 per mile, a savings of nearly 70%. For a driver covering 12,000 miles annually, this translates to roughly $1,000 per year in fuel savings. Over a 5-year period, fuel savings alone total $5,000.
      </p>

      <h3>Maintenance Savings</h3>
      <p>
        EVs require less maintenance because they have no engine oil, transmission fluid, spark plugs, timing belt, exhaust system, or complex multi-speed transmission. Annual EV maintenance averages $400-$600 versus $1,000-$1,400 for gas vehicles. Brake pads last longer on EVs thanks to regenerative braking. The main EV-specific maintenance items are tire rotation, cabin air filter replacement, and coolant checks.
      </p>

      <h3>Environmental Impact</h3>
      <p>
        Even accounting for electricity generation emissions, EVs produce significantly less CO2 than gas vehicles. A typical gas car emits 8,000-10,000 lbs of CO2 annually, while an EV on the US average grid produces 3,000-4,000 lbs. In states with cleaner electricity grids, the EV advantage is even greater. As the grid continues to shift toward renewable energy, the environmental benefit of EVs increases over time.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Is an electric car cheaper to own than a gas car?</h3>
      <p>In operating costs, yes. EVs are 60-70% cheaper to fuel and 30-50% cheaper to maintain. The break-even point for the higher purchase price is typically 3-7 years.</p>

      <h3>How much do you save on fuel with an EV?</h3>
      <p>About $1,000 per year for a typical driver at current prices. A gas car at 28 MPG costs ~$1,500/year vs ~$470 for an equivalent EV.</p>

      <h3>Are EVs cheaper to maintain than gas cars?</h3>
      <p>Yes. EV maintenance averages $400-$600 annually vs $1,000-$1,400 for gas vehicles, thanks to fewer moving parts and regenerative braking.</p>

      <h3>How much CO2 do EVs save?</h3>
      <p>EVs reduce CO2 by 50-70% on the US average grid. A gas car emits ~4.6 metric tons/year vs ~1.5-2.0 for an EV.</p>

      <h3>What is the break-even point?</h3>
      <p>If an EV costs $10,000 more and saves $2,000/year in operating costs, break-even is 5 years. Tax credits can bring this to 2-3 years.</p>

